Parse ecommerce catalogue product descriptions into structured lookup fields.

Input is JSON with an `items` array. Each item has:
- `item_index`
- `description`

For each item, return exactly one parsed object with the same `item_index`.

Rules:
- Descriptions usually look like: `the <product kind> from <brand> in the <family> line that has <constraints>`.
- Some descriptions are short product requests instead of that template. For
  those, keep descriptive words that are not clearly the brand, family, or
  product kind as constraints rather than broadening to the whole family.
- `brand` is the text after `from` and before `in the`.
- `product_kind` is the text after `the` and before `from`.
- `product_family` is the exact line/family text after `in the` and before `line`.
- `constraints` contains every explicit property constraint after `that has`.
- For excluded variants or properties, include the excluded feature as a constraint
  with `negated=true`. This includes wording such as `without ...`,
  `... excluded`, `not the ...`, and `outside ... listing`.
- Split constraints joined by commas, `and has`, and plain `and` when it introduces another property.
- Preserve property labels and values as short natural-language strings, e.g. `disc diameter 180 mm`, `mask type half mask`, `protection class p3`.
- Do not infer omitted constraints. Do not add catalogue data that was not present in the description.
- If a description is malformed, still return the best parse with empty strings/lists where needed. Do not invent fields.
